âŒ Step 3: Error Examples + Fixes
 Violation of CHECK (joining_date)
INSERT INTO job (employee_name, department, joining_date, salary)
VALUES ('Amit Singh', 'IT', '2018-12-30', 85000.00);
âŒ Error: Check constraint 'joining_date >= 2019-01-01' is violated
ðŸ› ï¸ Fix:
UPDATE job SET joining_date = '2019-01-05' WHERE employee_name = 'Amit Singh';

î·™î·š

2ï¸âƒ£ Missing NOT NULL Field
INSERT INTO job (department, joining_date, salary)
VALUES ('Marketing', '2023-03-01', 69000.00);


âŒ Error: Column 'employee_name' cannot be null
ðŸ› ï¸ Fix:
INSERT INTO job (employee_name, department, joining_date, salary)
VALUES ('Meena Gupta', 'Marketing', '2023-03-01', 69000.00);



3ï¸âƒ£ Negative Salary
INSERT INTO job (employee_name, department, joining_date, salary)
VALUES ('Vijay Rawat', 'Operations', '2023-01-20', -55000.00);


âŒ Error: Check constraint 'salary > 0' is violated
ðŸ› ï¸ Fix:
UPDATE job SET salary = 55000.00 WHERE employee_name = 'Vijay Rawat';



ðŸ” Step 4: View Table
SELECT * FROM job;



Youâ€™ll see the data including:
- Auto-generated employee_id
- Default city if not provided
- Error-free rows only

ðŸ§  What iâ€™ve Learned:
| Concept | Practical Example | 
| AUTO_INCREMENT | No need to type employee_id manually | 
| CHECK | Rules like salary > 0, joining_date >= 2019 | 
| NOT NULL | Mandatory fields like employee_name | 
| DEFAULT | Auto-fill city and experience | 
| Common Errors | Violation of CHECK, NOT NULL, wrong data types | 
